I&#39;m going to assume you mean you want the text at the bottom of your video but still overlapping the video.

When doing this kind of overlapping layout the key thing is to wrap the elements you&#39;re trying to overlap in a element (usually a div) that has position set to &quot;relative&quot;. That communicates to the browser that whatever layout happens to the children of this element should still happen relative to this element. 

Then you can set position &quot;absolute&quot; for the element(s) you want to move, in this case your text. From there you can use the four positional CSS properties (top, right, bottom and left) to move the inner elements around.

Here is a JSFiddle to show how that can be done. https://jsfiddle.net/0mbz4fh8/1/ 

Relevant CSS:  


    .annotated-video {
      position: relative;
    }
    
    .annotated-video__content {
      position: absolute;
      bottom: 0;
    }

If you rather wanted the text overlay to cover the video fully and still have the text at the bottom you can do so like this. https://jsfiddle.net/0mbz4fh8/2/

Relevant CSS:

    .annotated-video__content {
      position: absolute;
      /* Using both top and bottom stretches the container */
      top: 0;
      bottom: 0;
      /* Flex is a great tool to learn, here we create a column based flex container and tell it to justify (&quot;align&quot; the content at the end of the column, which is the bottom) */
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      justify-content: flex-end;
    }

You don&#39;t have to use position fixed. You can use `vw` and `vh` units. I included another element to wrap the video `.wrapper`. That uses `100%` width and `vh` for height to fill the screen. The video is then set to `object-fit` so it always remains full screen. I&#39;m assuming that you wanted the description to be directly after the video. If not, the second snippet is what you want.

